            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is Relative Fat Mass (RFM)?</h2>
              <p>
                Relative Fat Mass (RFM) is a simple index that estimates your
                body fat percentage using only your height and waist
                circumference. It was proposed as an alternative to Body Mass
                Index (BMI), because waist size better reflects how much fat you
                carry around your abdomen.
              </p>
              <p>
                RFM uses different formulas for men and women and has been shown
                in research to correlate well with body fat measured by DXA
                (dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry).
              </p>

              <h2>RFM formulas</h2>
              <p>
                RFM is calculated from the ratio of your height to your waist
                circumference:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>For men:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{RFM}_{male} = 64 - 20 \times
                  \dfrac{\text{height}}{\text{waist}}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3"><strong>For women:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{RFM}_{female} = 76 - 20 \times
                  \dfrac{\text{height}}{\text{waist}}\)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-3 text-gray-600">
                  Important: height and waist must be in the same units (both in
                  cm, or both in inches, etc.). The units cancel out in the
                  ratio.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example calculation</h3>
              <p>Suppose a man is 180&nbsp;cm tall with a 90&nbsp;cm waist:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \(\dfrac{\text{height}}{\text{waist}} = \dfrac{180}{90} =
                  2.0\)
                </p>
                <p>\(\text{RFM} = 64 - 20 \times 2.0 = 64 - 40 = 24\%\)</p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to measure your waist correctly</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>Stand upright, feet shoulder-width apart, relaxed.</li>
                <li>Find the level of your navel (belly button).</li>
                <li>
                  Wrap a flexible tape measure horizontally around your waist at
                  this level.
                </li>
                <li>Exhale normally (do not suck in your stomach).</li>
                <li>
                  Make sure the tape is snug but not compressing the skin.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Record the measurement to the nearest 0.5&nbsp;cm or
                  0.25&nbsp;inch.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Interpreting your RFM result</h2>
              <p>
                There is no single universal cut-off for RFM, but the ranges
                below are commonly used for adults. Our calculator uses these to
                give you a qualitative category.
              </p>

              <h3>Suggested RFM ranges for men</h3>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Category</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">RFM (men)</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Comment</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Low / very lean</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">&lt; 8%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Typical of competitive athletes; may be too low for some
                        people.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Healthy range</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">8–20%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Common target range for general health.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">High</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">20–25%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Increased risk of metabolic and cardiovascular issues.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">Very high</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">&gt; 25%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Obesity range; talk with a health professional about
                        weight management.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h3>Suggested RFM ranges for women</h3>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-100">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Category</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">RFM (women)</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left border-b">Comment</th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Low / very lean</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">&lt; 18%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Typical of athletes; too low can affect hormones and
                        fertility.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">Healthy range</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">18–30%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Common target range for general health.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">High</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">30–35%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2 border-b">
                        Increased risk of metabolic and cardiovascular issues.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">Very high</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">&gt; 35%</td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Obesity range; consider medical advice and lifestyle
                        changes.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>RFM vs BMI</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>BMI</strong> uses only height and weight; it does not
                  distinguish between fat and muscle.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>RFM</strong> uses waist circumference, which reflects
                  abdominal fat and fat distribution.
                </li>
                <li>
                  RFM can better identify people with normal BMI but high waist
                  fat (so‑called “normal weight obesity”).
                </li>
                <li>Both are screening tools, not diagnostic tests.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations of RFM</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  It is an estimate, not a direct measurement of body fat.
                </li>
                <li>Accuracy depends on correct waist measurement.</li>
                <li>
                  May be less accurate for very muscular individuals or those
                  with unusual body proportions.
                </li>
                <li>Developed for adults; not validated for children.</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>When to seek professional advice</h2>
              <p>
                If your RFM falls in the high or very high range, or if you have
                other risk factors (family history, high blood pressure,
                abnormal blood tests), consider speaking with a doctor or
                registered dietitian. They can perform more precise assessments
                and help you design a safe plan for weight and health
                management.
              </p>
            </section>

            <!-- FAQ -->
            <section class="mt-8">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">
                Relative Fat Mass (RFM) – FAQ
              </h2>
              <div class="space-y-3" id="faq-container">
                <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg">
                  <button
                    type="button"
                    class="w-full flex justify-between items-center px-4 py-3 text-left faq-question"
                  >
                    <span class="font-medium text-gray-800"
                      >What is Relative Fat Mass (RFM)?</span
                    >
                    <span class="ml-2 text-gray-500">+</span>
                  </button>
                  <div
                    class="px-4 pb-3 hidden faq-answer text-sm text-gray-700"
                  >
                    Relative Fat Mass (RFM) is an estimate of your body fat
                    percentage based on your height and waist circumference. It
                    was proposed as a simpler, often more accurate alternative
                    to BMI because it directly incorporates a measure of central
                    fat (waist size).
